That in all seriousness is the reason  is not an officially recognized abbreviation for grams: Gm is gigameters, gm is gram meters. The latter pairing pops up occasionally in vector physics- it's a less convoluted way of writing mN⋅s2. It comes up when you're doing things like calculating the total change in momentum in a system over a given time period or similarly odd things. Grams per meter is g/m, and people who refer to that as gram meters are incorrect in doing so.





